06723nam a22014415i 9781400848867DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20132014nju    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979746011  a97814008488677 a10.1515/97814008488672doi  a(DE-B1597)453965  a(OCoLC)862048740  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aN72.S6 7aSOC0030002bisacsh04a701.032231 aWengrow, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Origins of Monsters :bImage and Cognition in the First Age of Mechanical Reproduction /cDavid Wengrow.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2013] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource (184 p.) :b10 halftones. 23 line illus. 1 map.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Rostovtzeff Lectures ;v200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Image and Economy in the Ancient World: The Bronze Age of Mikhail Rostovtzeff -- t2. Materials for an Epidemiology of Culture -- t3. The Hidden Shaman: Fictive Anatomy in Paleolithic and Neolithic Art -- t4. Urban Creations: The Cultural Ecology of Composite Animals -- t5. Counterintuitive Images and the Mechanical Arts -- t6. Modes of Image Transfer: Transformative, Integrative, Protective -- tConclusion. Persistent, but Not Primordial: Emergent Properties of Cognition -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt has often been claimed that "monsters"--supernatural creatures with bodies composed from multiple species--play a significant part in the thought and imagery of all people from all times. The Origins of Monsters advances an alternative view. Composite figurations are intriguingly rare and isolated in the art of the prehistoric era. Instead it was with the rise of cities, elites, and cosmopolitan trade networks that "monsters" became widespread features of visual production in the ancient world. Showing how these fantastic images originated and how they were transmitted, David Wengrow identifies patterns in the records of human image-making and embarks on a search for connections between mind and culture. Wengrow asks: Can cognitive science explain the potency of such images? Does evolutionary psychology hold a key to understanding the transmission of symbols? How is our making and perception of images influenced by institutions and technologies? Wengrow considers the work of art in the first age of mechanical reproduction, which he locates in the Middle East, where urban life began. Comparing the development and spread of fantastic imagery across a range of prehistoric and ancient societies, including Mesopotamia, Egypt, Greece, and China, he explores how the visual imagination has been shaped by a complex mixture of historical and universal factors. Examining the reasons behind the dissemination of monstrous imagery in ancient states and empires, The Origins of Monsters sheds light on the relationship between culture and cognition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAnimals, Mythical, in art. 0aArchaeology and art. 0aArt and societyxHistory. 0aArt, Ancient. 0aArt, Prehistoric. 0aCognition and culture. 0aImagery (Psychology). 0aMonsters in artxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh  aBronze Age civilization.  aBronze Age.  aChina.  aIron Age.  aMikhail Rostovtzeff.  aOld World.  aPaleolithic art.  aRudolph Wittkower.  aScandinavia.  aTiryns.  aancient world.  aanimal figures.  aanimals.  aart.  acognition.  acomposite animals.  acomposite figures.  acomposites.  acounterfactual images.  acounterintuitive images.  acounterintuitiveness.  acultural ecology.  acultural tr